'''Miriam O'Callaghan''' (Miriam N<U+00ED> Cheallach<U+00E1>in) became the 26th president of the [[Camogie Association]] when she defeated [[Helen McAleevy]] of [[Down GAA#Camogie|Down]] 39-27 at the 2003 congress in the Arklow Bay Hotel.<ref>{{cite book | last = Moran | first = Mary | authorlink = Mary Moran (camogie) | title = A Game of Our Own: The History of Camogie | publisher = Cumann Cam<U+00F3>ga<U+00ED>ochta | year = 2011 | location = Dublin, Ireland | pages = 460}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/sportslines-489588.html|title=Irish Independent Mar 30 2003}}</ref>

==Background==
From [[Tullamore GAA#Camogie|Tullamore]], she chaired [[Offaly GAA#Camogie|Offaly County Camogie Board]] and refereed the 1991 and 1993 [[All-Ireland Senior Camogie Championship|All Ireland senior finals]].

==Presidency==
Her presidency was distinguished by new marketing initiatives including a brash and high-profile centenary <U+201C><U+2018>chicks with sticks<U+201D><U+2018> campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/hurling/liberated-chicks-with-attitude-205614.html|title=Irish Independent: Liberated 'Chicks' with attitude Sept 20 2003}}</ref> She launched the 2004-08 strategic plan that increased camogie<U+2019>s club base by 20pc, wand led to new county boards being established in [[Mayo GAA#Camogie|Mayo]], [[Kerry GAA#Camogie|Kerry]] and [[Donegal GAA#Camogie|Donegal]]. At the end of her presidency club numbers reach an all time high of 515.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/kfkfojqlaukf/rss2/|title=Irish Examiner Mar 27 2010}}</ref>

During her presidency the Camogie Association appointed a full-time National Development co-ordinator and two regional development co-ordinators.

She renegotiated, with the assistance of Leinster Chairman [[Liam O'Neill]], the twinning of the camogie finals with the under-21 hurling final, an arrangement that lasted from 2006 to 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/camogie-historic-final-deal-225765.html|title=Irish Independent Dec 14 2005}}</ref>

She initiated moves to integrate the camogie association and GAA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/female-relations-forge-stronger-bond-in-the-gaas-family-266050.html|title=Irish Independent Apr 27 2006}}</ref>

In 2003 the first full-time sponsorship and finance manager was appointed and the [[All-Ireland Senior Club Camogie Championship|All-Ireland Junior Club Championship]] was inaugurated and won by [[Crossmaglen Rangers GAC|Crossmaglen]].

==Centenary==
In 2004 she unveiled a plaque at Navan to celebrate the centenary of the Camogie Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/hurling/camogie--galway-class-sees-antrim-draw-blank-163654.html|title=Irish Independent July 19, 2004}}</ref> The Association celebrated 100 years with a Gala Banquet, the announcement of the Team of the Century and numerous other events. The first [[Camogie All Stars Awards|All Star team]] was announced in December 2004. As part of the centenary celebrations, RTE covered the [[All-Ireland Senior Camogie Championship|All Ireland semi-finals]] live on television for the first time.<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/sport/hurling/rte-going-live-for-semis-183096.html Irish Independent: RTE going live for semis, Feb 4 2004]</ref>

==Other roles==
While Camogie President she was appointed to serve on the Broadcasting Complaints Commission.<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/bcc-heralds-bad-days-for-broadcasters-133160.html Sunday Independent Aug 6 2006]</ref> After her presidency she was elected Chair of Offaly Sports Partnership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.offalysports.ie/News?Id=286|title=Offaly Sports Partnership May 5, 2010}}</ref>

